>independent energy consultants Delta-ee to demonstrate and provide evidence of how LP Gas could contribute to reducing carbon in the off grid heat sector. In its modelling it concluded that:</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">“</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">A mix of low carbon LP Gas technologies could deliver significan</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">t carbon savings by 2030.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">”</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-style:italic; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">1.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">Excluding m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">ixed solutions is unrealistic: n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">ew renewable technologies, especially those that are weather dependent need to be backed by constant fuel sources.  Consumers need reliable heat power and the reality is that fossil fue</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">ls will be a part of this mix.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">1.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">Encourage consumers towards prag</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">matic but efficient solutions: as a clean burning,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> lower carbon, gaseous fuel, LPG has a role to play to drive down emissions and can easily work in combination with other fuels and technologi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">es as consumers move to improve their homes’ efficiency.  Government should be helping consumers to take up the cleanest and most efficient options which allow them the reliability that they need.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">1.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">Now and in the future: LP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> has a greater role to play t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">o drive down emissions and can easily work in combination with other fuels and technologies as consumers move to improve their homes’ efficiency.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">1.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">When off grid reliability is key, options where there is integration with the building’s existing heating </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">system ensures continuous energy for heat.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.13pt; padding-left:4.87pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">About </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">UKLPG and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">LP Gas</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">2.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">UKLPG is the one voice of the LP Gas industry in the UK, representing an industry worth over £750 million to the economy and employing over 10,000 people.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">2.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">UKLPG represents all the major LPG distribution companies, retailers and equipment suppliers in the UK and a number of producers. Member companies cover over 95% of the total LPG sales in the UK.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">2.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">LP Gas is sold into bulk tanks at customers’ locations in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> off grid areas, or in cylinders for portable use throughout the UK. LP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> is used in rural areas of the UK as a source of domestic and commercial heating and cooking, as well as agricultural grain drying and poultry rearing, and finally as a transport fu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">el.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">2.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">Propane and Butane gases, collectively known as LPG (Liquefied Petroleum Gas) are sourced either from separating the products from natural gas streams, or from oil refinery processes. LP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">is a relatively small part of the barrel, some 2-3% of the o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">utput of refined products, but is used extensively for off grid domestic and commercial heating - as is portable bottled gas - in industrial processes and in the petro-chemical industry. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">2.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">A total of 3.5 million tonnes of LP Gas is used in the UK, of which</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> two thirds is used in the petro-chemical industry and the remaining third sold into the inland heating and industrial market. Two thirds of LP Gas produced in the UK comes from refinery production versus one third from gas separation.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">2.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">LP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> is cost effe</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">ctive due to its efficiency.  In its liquid form it is also so compact that one unit of gas holds the fuel of 270 units of gas.  LPG can be up to five times more efficient than traditional fuels.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.13pt; padding-left:4.87pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Our Response</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">3.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">Consumption of energy for heat in the home is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> on a downward trend with promising new technologies offering further efficiency gains.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> The priority has to be to maintain this trend and the good news is that gas</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> - including liquefied petroleum gas -</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> technology still has an enormous amount to offer. For </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">example, two thirds of properties still have older non-condensing boilers and therefore still have significant savings available at relatively low cost.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> There</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> is also a raft of exciting new technologies coming on to the market which will further accelerate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> the decline in energy consumption and carbon emissions and can be used in off gas grid areas as well. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">3.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">Several LP Gas technology options will be available in the next few years that can deliver carbon savings in rural buildings out to 2030. Today boiler </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">plus options</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">are already available at relatively low cost for domestic properties with hybrid technologies recently available, and commercial gas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">absorption</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">heat pumps </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">(GAHPs) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">all being sold with LP Gas options.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">3.3.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">A study into the role of LP Gas to heat rural homes and businesses was carried out by Delta Energy Environment. The resulting report, entitled </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Opportunity for Low Carbon LP Gas in Rural Heating to 2030</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> reviewed existing and new heating technologies such as hybrid air source heat pumps, 18 kw LP Gas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">GAHPs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, fuel cell micro combined heat and power, engine micro combined heat and power, boiler plus solar thermal, boiler plus flue gas heat recovery, and boil</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">er plus controls. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">3.4.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Delta-ee found that in addition to the 42% energy savings from low-carbon LP Gas technologies, that in old detached properties, LP Gas </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">GAHPs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> deliver savings of 3.5 tonnes of CO2 per year. Rural hotels show a savings of 10 tonnes per yea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">r.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">3.5.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">According to Delta-ee </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">modelling for a detached pre-1900 property there are cost saving, as well as carbon saving benefits when using LP Gas. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Running cost savings are a high priority for customer decision making LP Gas heat pumps offer a very attractive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> reduction in annual running costs (~£1,200 per year). Hybrid ASHPs &amp; boiler plus controls are quite attractive delivering savings of ~£350 / yr. For other technologies, savings are more modest at &lt;£300 per year.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:'Palatino Linotype'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">3.6.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Gas Absorption Heat Pumps – a renewable ga</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">s technology which can be retrofitted on to a home’s existing central heating system</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> has already been recognised </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">as a key low carbon technology </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">in the latest DECC paper </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">The Future of Heating- Meeting the Challenge</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">3.7.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">Significant improvements in energy effic</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">iency in the housing stock can be achieved through replacement of inefficient appliances by technologies such as the condensing boiler, which utilises the latent heat of water produced from the burning of fuel, in addition to the standard sensible heat, to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> increase its efficiency. Condensing technology, an established and cost-effective solution has a demonstrated potential to increase boilers efficiency by 15-20 percent as compared to their conventional equivalents. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 36pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">3.8.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">LPG and solar or wind energy are a natural partnership: Solar and wind are great examples of how LPG can offer reliability and security to renewables. LPG can be used as a primary or complementary source of energy, helping to overcome the intermittent natu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">re of these energy sources.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> These modern systems —often referred to as hybrids — combine the reliability of a conventional fuel with the numerous benefits of renewable energy to provide warm water for millions of consumers across Europe. Hybrid solutions c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">an also be desig</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">ned to meet space-heating needs.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">3.9.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">There are potential </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">risks</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> associated with the promotion of fuels like biomass as these may reduce carbon dioxide emissions while contributing to the problem of climate change through their high black carbon</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> emissions.  The United Nations Economic Commission for Europe (UNECE) noted the risk of biomass resulting in an increase in black carbon emissions in a 2010 report [AEGPL].</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">3.10.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">LP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">G</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> produces low levels of particle and NOx emissions, meaning that it does no</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">t pollute the air as much as many other energy sources.  For three priority pollutants; hydrocarbons,  nitrous oxides  and particle matter, as well as on carbon monoxide, toxics and heavy metals, gaseous fuels’ air pollution footprints are lower than those</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> of liquid fuels (heating oil and residual oil) and dramatically lower than those of solid fuels (coal and wood). [LPG and Air Quality: A Scientific Review, Atlantic consulting].</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">3.11.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">Biomass is proving to be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> risky</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">: a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> switch to biomass fuelled heating – as some policies seem to be encouraging - could increase black carbon and particulate emissions and perversely lead</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> to increased air pollution</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">, an issue which government health figures already</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">attribute to the cause of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">up to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> 80,000</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> deaths</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> per year</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">3.12.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">Electricity should not be considered a green alternative until cleaner methods of generation are developed. Currently the facts suggest that electricity will remain reliant on fossil fuels for the foreseeable future. The r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">ole of coal in electricity production in the EU-27, is projected to decline only modestly, from 26% in 2010 to 22% in 2030. [AEGPL]</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">3.13.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">When off grid reliability is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">important;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> options where there is integration with the building’s existing heating system ensu</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">res continuous energy for heat.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 13.13pt; padding-left:4.87pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Our Recommendations</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">4.1.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">Government needs to r</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">ecognise the role of a “balanced approach”, and to gain consumer momentum </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt"> all low carbon alternatives should be included in the UK Policy framework. Government should take positive action to include LP Gas low carbon alternatives in the heat sector to help drive down carbon emissions while supporting the infrastructure transiti</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">on while electricity is decarbonised out to 2030. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt; text-indent:-21.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">4.2.</span><span style="font:7.0pt 'Times New Roman'">&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">Through policies such as the Renewable Heat Incentive and the Green Deal encourage consumers towards pragmatic but efficient solutions. LP Gas is a natural partner to some renewable technologies, and can </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">help overcome some of the short term barriers for consumer transition. It has an existing supply chain in place as well as an industry which has significant expertise in the unique hard to treat properties found off grid.  </span></p><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 39.6pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt; font-weight:bold">Delta-EE Report</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">A copy of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10.5pt">executive summary of this report is available in PDF format via our website at </span><a h